The paper deals with cell tracking in biological images, which is a common problem in computer vision and machine learning. The proposed method uses motion and position maps to jointly represent detection and association, which is a technique commonly used in computer vision and machine learning for object tracking. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper also proposes a new method for multi-object tracking, which involves machine learning and optimization techniques, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) likely sub-categories as well. The paper also deals with dense environments, which is a common problem in multimedia and video processing, making cs.MM (Multimedia) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper uses motion flow to track cell migration, which is a technique commonly used in neural networks, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) a possible sub-category as well.
